  description="Test and debug regular expressions with real-time matching. See all matches, capture groups, and index positions instantly in your browser."
  toolName="Regex Tester"
  toolUrl="https://oortcraft.dev/tools/regex-tester"
  faq={[
    { question: 'Is my data safe?', answer: 'Yes. All regex testing happens entirely in your browser using JavaScript. No data is sent to any server.' },
    { question: 'Which flags are supported?', answer: 'The tool supports g (global), i (case insensitive), m (multiline), and s (dot all) flags. You can combine multiple flags.' },
    { question: 'Why does my regex match unexpectedly?', answer: 'Common pitfalls include forgetting to escape special characters like . * + ? ( ) [ ] { } ^ $ | \\, or not using the global flag when you expect multiple matches.' },
    { question: 'What is a capture group?', answer: 'A capture group is a part of the pattern wrapped in parentheses (). It lets you extract specific parts of a match. For example, (\\d+)-(\\d+) applied to 2024-01 captures 2024 and 01 as separate groups.' },
    { question: 'How do I match a literal dot?', answer: 'Use \\. instead of .. In regex, an unescaped dot matches any character. To match a literal period — for example in a file extension or IP address — you must escape it: \\.txt or \\d+\\.\\d+\\.\\d+\\.\\d+.' },
    { question: 'What is catastrophic backtracking?', answer: 'Catastrophic backtracking occurs when a regex engine explores an exponentially large number of paths through a pattern before concluding there is no match. It is triggered by nested quantifiers such as (a+)+ applied to a string of repeated characters followed by a non-matching character. The engine tries every combination of how the inner and outer quantifiers can split the input, leading to execution times that grow exponentially with input length. Avoid patterns that have multiple adjacent quantifiers covering overlapping character sets.' },
    { question: 'Can I use this tool for languages other than JavaScript?', answer: 'The core regex syntax — character classes, quantifiers, anchors, and groups — works across most languages including Python, Java, Ruby, and PHP. However, some features are JavaScript-specific: named capture groups use (?<name>...) syntax which differs slightly in older engines, lookbehind assertions have limited support in some environments, and the s (dot all) flag is called re.DOTALL in Python. Use this tool to build and verify your pattern logic, then adapt the syntax to your target language if needed.' },
  ]}
